<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>THE ECONOMIC COST OF TERRORISM </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> After the horrific attacks in Paris, it is an issue that <b>policy makers are grappling with</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/business/dealbook/the-fallout-from-attacks-is-measured-in-more-than-stock-markets.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Research shows that <b>gross domestic product barely budged</b> after the Madrid train bombings in 2004 and the bombs in London the year after. Consumption in the United States was stable after the Sept. 11 attacks, but investment fell. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Stocks markets <b>typically recover</b> within weeks and on Monday, they were flat in Europe and up more than 1 percent in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But this reaction may belie the <b>true cost of terrorism</b>. Many regard the events in Paris as part of a continuum. The attacks could also have far-reaching implications for the future of the eurozone and companies there. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They could add to the <b>pressure to close borders</b> and reignite a debate about privacy and surveillance that will have a big effect on technology companies. The indirect costs are difficult to measure. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One reminder that the scale of economic damage could be much higher is an academic study that showed that <b>Israelâs per capita G.D.P.</b> would have been 8.6 percent higher in the period from 1994 to 2003 had there been peace.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>SETBACKS CAST HARSH LIGHT ON MANHATTAN PROSECUTOR</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The spotlight on the district attorney of Manhattan has been more intense since he suffered <b>several setbacks in white-collar trials</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/18/business/dealbook/recent-setbacks-cast-harsh-light-on-cyrus-vance-the-manhattan-prosecutor.html">Matthew Goldstein reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lawyers have been wondering whether the district attorney, Cyrus R. Vance Jr.,  made financial trials too complex and whether he has been aggressively pursuing matters that might have been <b>better off treated as civil disputes</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Vance conceded that the trial of three former executives of the once-mighty law firm Dewey &#038; LeBoeuf could have been handled better. The men were accused of orchestrating an accounting fraud and he said that if there was a new trial for them, it would have to be &#8220;<b>simpler and shorter</b>.â  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The trial took four months and the jury spent 21 days grappling with the 151 charges against the men. <b>The deadlock now means that Mr. Vance has to decide</b> whether the men should be retried and how to streamline any new proceedings. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He is expected to decide by Dec. 7, when the parties are scheduled to return to court. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In another setback for Mr. Vance, in June, a <b>jury acquitted two senior officers</b> of Abacus Federal Savings Bank in a mortgage fraud case. Mr. Vance charged the Chinatown bank, and more than a dozen employees, with participating in a âsystematicâ scheme to sell fraudulent mortgages to Fannie Mae. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Questions have emerged over the trial readiness of his prosecutors after prosecutors working for Mr. Vance said the trial had been compromised by &#8220;<b>unanticipated witness issues and evidentiary issues</b>.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The admission is of <b>little comfort for some of the defendants</b> who have spent more than five years dealing with the investigation. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf you care more about the press conference than the proof, you end up charging people and institutions that you shouldnât and <b>overreaching in terms of theories</b>,â said Kevin R. Puvalowski, the main lawyer for Abacus. âMy clients spent millions of dollars on this investigation and trial, and it seriously damaged their business for years.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Vance declined to elaborate on the court filing but said his office had <b>secured guilty pleas</b> from eight employees of the bank, which was evidence that crimes were committed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe have not shied away from tough or challenging cases,â Mr. Vance said. âWe are going to do tough cases, and some of those cases the jury is not going to agree with us. That is the <b>reality of prosecution</b>.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A ROCKY QUARTER FOR HEDGE FUNDS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Thousands of hedge funds have disclosed which stocks they bought in regulatory disclosures to the Securities and Exchange Commission for the third quarter and <b>many of them lost money</b> for their clients, </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/business/dealbook/filings-show-rocky-quarter-for-many-hedge-funds.html?ref=dealbook">Alexandra Stevenson and Matthew Goldstein report in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Grantham Mayo Van Otterloo, the large hedge fund that Jeremy Grantham helped found, increased its <b>stake in Valeant</b> just as it came under siege. Viking Global, the hedge fund led by O. Andreas Halvorsen, also added Valeant stock to its portfolio. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ValueAct, the multibillion-dollar firm founded by Jeffrey W. Ubben, is the top shareholder. John A. Paulson also holds 8.9 million shares, though he sold 110,000.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The filings are an imperfect window into firmsâ finances, but they do show that Wall Streetâs biggest and wealthiest money managers <b>invest in herds</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Leon G. Cooperman of Omega Advisors, Daniel S. Loeb of Third Point, York Capital Management and Coatue Management were among the investors who added <b>Kraft Heinz</b> as a new position in their portfolios during the quarter. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Loeb, Citadel, York Capital and Jana Partners, the hedge fund founded by Barry Rosenstein, all held stakes in <b>Baxter International</b>, the medical equipment maker. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Starwood Hotels and the <b>renewable energy company SunEdison</b> were two other favorites among investors. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Walmart</b> will hold a conference call on its third-quarter results at 7 a.m. Data on <b>consumer prices</b> in October will be released at 8:30 a.m. <b>Industrial production</b> data will be released at 9:15 a.m. The latest <b>NAHB/Wells Fargo housing market index</b> data will be released at 10 a.m. The <b>Financial Services Committee</b> will hold a hearing at 10 a.m. titled âDodd-Frank Five Years Later: What Have We Learned from Conflict Minerals Reporting?â The second day of the <b>Global Financial Leadership Conference</b> starts at 9 a.m. Speakers include Dick Costolo, the former chief of Twitter, and Elizabeth Holmes, the chief of Theranos. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>MARRIOTTâS DEAL TO BUY STARWOOD HOTELS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Marriott International was not among the rumored suitors when Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide put itself up for sale, but it looks as if the decline in hotel stocks and stronger competition from Airbnb  have made <b>consolidation seem more attractive</b>,<br />
<a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/business/marriott-to-buy-starwood-hotels.html">Leslie Picker reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Hyatt was a competitive bidder</b> almost to the end, but ultimately the Starwood board thought Marriottâs stock had greater potential. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Marriott announced that it would acquire Starwood for <b>$11.9 billion</b> in stock and $340 million in cash. The deal would create the worldâs largest hotel company, with more than 5,500 owned or franchised hotels. The agreement represented a premium of about 6 percent above the average of where Starwoodâs stock had traded in the 20 days before Nov. 13. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <b>premium was lower than expected</b>, given the competitive sales process, and Starwoodâs shares fell, while Marriottâs gained.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Marriottâs chief executive, Arne M. Sorenson, said the deal promoted growth and value creation, but it was <b>not evident from the figures</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/business/dealbook/marriotts-deal-for-starwood-looks-defensive.html">Jeffrey Goldfarb writes in Breakingviews.</a> The deal looks decidedly defensive. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares in Starwood and its rivals have slipped steadily, despite regular consolidation. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Marriott is paying a <b>premium under 20 percent</b>, worth about $1.9 billion, based on its stock price before media reports of potential buyers in October. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It anticipates about <b>$200 million in annual cost savings</b>. Once taxed and capitalized, these could be worth some $1.3 billion today.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Marriott is paying more in premium than is justified by its stated savings, and Starwood investors have a fairly stingy premium to fall back on, Mr. Goldfarb writes. There <b>may well be pushback</b> from hedge funds invested in Starwood. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
